Explain the purpose of the isinstance() function and when it might be beneficial in a Python program. Provide an example.

The isinstance() function in Python checks if an object belongs to a specified class or data type.
It's useful for type checking, conditional branching, and polymorphism. Here's a concise example:

class Animal: pass
class Dog(Animal): pass
class Cat(Animal): pass

dog = Dog()
cat = Cat()

print(isinstance(dog, Dog))  # True
print(isinstance(dog, Animal))  # True
print(isinstance(cat, Dog))  # False
print(isinstance(cat, Cat))  # True
print(isinstance(cat, Animal))  # True


This code demonstrates the usage of isinstance() to check object types within a class hierarchy.
